    "type": "multiple-choice",
    "passage": "Read the passage and answer the questions.\n\n**The Moonlight Garden**\n*by Elena Brooks*\n\nAt the back of the town library stood a narrow courtyard surrounded by brick walls. Most visitors hurried past it without looking twice. During the day, the courtyard seemed plain: a few benches, a stone birdbath, and several empty planting beds outlined with old boards.\n\nBut at night, said Mrs. Alvarez, the librarian, the courtyard could become something special.\n\nShe shared her idea during the student helper meeting in early spring. \"I want to create a moonlight garden,\" she said. \"A place with flowers that shine pale in the evening and plants with silver leaves that catch the light.\"\n\nNoah raised his hand. \"Why would people visit a garden at night?\"\n\nMrs. Alvarez smiled. \"Because some things are easier to notice when the world gets quiet.\"\n\nMost of the helpers liked the idea right away. Talia was not so sure. She preferred loud projects with bright posters and cheering crowds. A garden sounded slow.\n\nStill, she signed up to help.\n\nEvery Wednesday after school, the helpers met in the courtyard. Mrs. Alvarez showed them how to loosen the soil and mix in compost. Mr. Chen from the plant nursery donated lamb's ear, white petunias, evening primrose, and tall grasses that whispered in the breeze. The students added smooth stones along the paths and painted old flowerpots deep blue.\n\nAt first, the garden did not look like much. The plants were small, and the courtyard still felt dusty and bare.\n\n\"It's like waiting for a story to start,\" Noah said.\n\nTalia shrugged. \"I hope it gets to the interesting part soon.\"\n\nWeeks passed. The students watered, weeded, and tied labels to wooden sticks. They also hung tiny metal bells beside the gate and strung soft white lights along the wall. One afternoon, Talia noticed that the lamb's ear leaves looked almost silver. Another day, she bent to smell the primrose and caught a sweet scent that seemed strongest near sunset.\n\nBy June, the courtyard had changed. White blossoms glowed against the dark soil. Pale stones curved through the beds like a small river. The grasses lifted and bowed when the evening wind moved through them. When the lights switched on, the whole place seemed to float.\n\nMrs. Alvarez invited families to the library for the opening night. She asked the student helpers to guide visitors through the garden and read short poems aloud.\n\nThat evening, Talia arrived just as the sun was dropping behind the roof of the library. She stopped at the gate and stared.\n\nThe courtyard looked larger than she remembered. Fireflies blinked above the grass. The white flowers shone in the deep blue air. Parents whispered as if they had stepped into a chapel. A toddler reached for the bells and laughed when they chimed softly.\n\nNoah came up beside Talia. \"Interesting enough yet?\" he asked.\n\nTalia did not answer right away. She was watching the moon rise above the wall.\n\n\"Yeah,\" she said finally. \"I think quiet things can be interesting too.\"\n\nLater, after the visitors left, the student helpers sat on the benches eating slices of pear tart from the bakery next door. No one hurried to leave. The courtyard held the cool air, the flower scent, and the moonlight all at once.\n\nMrs. Alvarez looked around at the garden and then at the students. \"You gave this place a second life,\" she said.\n\nTalia touched one of the silvery leaves beside her bench. For once, she did not feel like saying anything. The garden already seemed to be speaking for itself.\n\n---\n\nRead the passage and answer the questions.\n\n**Why Wetlands Matter**\n*adapted from environmental education sources*\n\nWetlands are places where land is covered by shallow water for part or all of the year. Some wetlands are marshes full of grasses, while others are swamps with trees and shrubs. At first glance, a wetland may look muddy, still, or even empty. In fact, wetlands are some of the busiest and most important ecosystems on Earth.\n\n**Homes for Wildlife**\n\nMany animals depend on wetlands. Frogs lay eggs in calm water. Ducks and herons nest among reeds. Fish use wetland areas as safe places to rest or grow before moving into deeper rivers, lakes, or oceans. Insects, turtles, and mammals also rely on wetlands for food and shelter.\n\n**Natural Sponges**\n\nWetlands act like giant sponges during storms. When heavy rain falls, wetlands can hold extra water and slow flooding. This helps protect nearby neighborhoods, farms, and roads. Later, some of that water slowly moves back into streams and underground supplies.\n\n**Cleaning the Water**\n\nWetlands can also help clean water. As water moves through wetland plants and soil, mud and pollution can get trapped. This does not remove every harmful material, but it can improve water quality. Scientists often compare wetlands to natural filters.\n\n**Changing Over Time**\n\nWetlands are always changing. A wetland may grow larger after rainy years and shrink during dry seasons. New plants move in. Animal populations rise and fall. Because wetlands are connected to weather, water, and living things, they are always in motion even when they appear quiet.\n\n**Why Wetlands Need Protection**\n\nFor many years, people drained wetlands to build roads, stores, and neighborhoods. Some wetlands were filled with dirt because people did not understand how useful they were. Today, many communities protect wetlands by limiting pollution, restoring native plants, and creating boardwalks so visitors can learn without damaging the habitat.\n\nProtecting wetlands helps both wildlife and people. A healthy wetland can reduce flooding, improve water quality, and support many kinds of life all at once.",
